TY  - JOUR
T1  - Rising Markups and the Role of Consumer                         Preferences
AU  - Döpper, Hendrik
AU  - MacKay, Alexander
AU  - Miller, Nathan H.
AU  - Stiebale, Joel
Y1  - 2025/02/24
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/735510
DO  - 10.1086/735510
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2462
EP  - 2505
VL  - 133
IS  - 8
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We analyze the evolution of markups for consumer products in the United States from 2006 to 2019. Using detailed data on prices and quantities for products in more than 100 distinct categories, we obtain a panel of markups, marginal costs, and flexible consumer preferences. Our empirical strategy uses separate random coefficients logit models for each category and year and an assumption that firms set prices to maximize profits. We find that markups increased by about 30% on average over the sample period. We attribute this change to decreases in marginal costs and a decline in consumer price sensitivity.
AB  - We analyze the evolution of markups for consumer products in the United States from 2006 to 2019. Using detailed data on prices and quantities for products in more than 100 distinct categories, we obtain a panel of markups, marginal costs, and flexible consumer preferences. Our empirical strategy uses separate random coefficients logit models for each category and year and an assumption that firms set prices to maximize profits. We find that markups increased by about 30% on average over the sample period. We attribute this change to decreases in marginal costs and a decline in consumer price sensitivity.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/735510
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/735510
