TY  - JOUR
T1  - Minimum Wage and Individual Worker Productivity: Evidence from a Large US Retailer
AU  - Coviello, Decio
AU  - Deserranno, Erika
AU  - Persico, Nicola
Y1  - 2022/04/12
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/720397
DO  - 10.1086/720397
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2315
EP  - 2360
VL  - 130
IS  - 9
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We study workers who are employed by a large US retailer, work in many store locations, and are paid based on performance. By means of a border-discontinuity analysis, we document that workers become more productive and are terminated less often after a minimum wage increase. These effects are stronger among workers whose pay is more often supported by the minimum wage. However, when workers are monitored less intensely, the minimum wage depresses productivity. We interpret these findings through an efficiency wage model. After a minimum wage increase, profits decrease, and a calibration exercise suggests that worker welfare increases.
AB  - We study workers who are employed by a large US retailer, work in many store locations, and are paid based on performance. By means of a border-discontinuity analysis, we document that workers become more productive and are terminated less often after a minimum wage increase. These effects are stronger among workers whose pay is more often supported by the minimum wage. However, when workers are monitored less intensely, the minimum wage depresses productivity. We interpret these findings through an efficiency wage model. After a minimum wage increase, profits decrease, and a calibration exercise suggests that worker welfare increases.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/720397
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/720397
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Neolithic Agricultural Revolution and the Origins of Private Property
AU  - Bowles, Samuel
AU  - Choi, Jung-Kyoo
Y1  - 2018/11/28
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2019/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/701789
DO  - 10.1086/701789
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2186
EP  - 2228
VL  - 127
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Familiar explanations of why hunter-gatherers first took up farming?superior labor productivity, population pressure, or adverse climate?receive little support from recent evidence. Farming would be an unlikely choice without possession-based private property, which appears to have existed among rare groups of sedentary hunter-gatherers who became the first farmers. Our model shows that among them, farming could have benefited first adopters because private possession was more readily established and defended for cultivated crops and domesticated animals than for the diffuse wild resources on which hunter-gatherers relied, thus explaining how farming could have been introduced even without a productivity advantage.
AB  - Familiar explanations of why hunter-gatherers first took up farming?superior labor productivity, population pressure, or adverse climate?receive little support from recent evidence. Farming would be an unlikely choice without possession-based private property, which appears to have existed among rare groups of sedentary hunter-gatherers who became the first farmers. Our model shows that among them, farming could have benefited first adopters because private possession was more readily established and defended for cultivated crops and domesticated animals than for the diffuse wild resources on which hunter-gatherers relied, thus explaining how farming could have been introduced even without a productivity advantage.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/701789
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/701789
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Soil Heterogeneity, Social Learning, and the Formation of                         Close-Knit Communities
AU  - Raz, Itzchak Tzachi
Y1  - 2025/02/24
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/735506
DO  - 10.1086/735506
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2643
EP  - 2691
VL  - 133
IS  - 8
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper examines how environmental heterogeneity influences the formation of close-knit communities. I provide support for the social learning hypothesis, which posits that diverse environmental conditions limited American farmers? ability to learn from neighbors, weakening communal ties. I document a negative county-level association between soil heterogeneity and close-knit communities. Using individual-level data on nineteenth-century domestic migrants, I show that this association is not driven by selective in-migration and document farmers? cultural adaptation using a difference-in-differences framework. Focusing on mechanisms, I show that soil heterogeneity slowed farmers? agricultural learning and prompted those who depended on social networks to migrate elsewhere.
AB  - This paper examines how environmental heterogeneity influences the formation of close-knit communities. I provide support for the social learning hypothesis, which posits that diverse environmental conditions limited American farmers? ability to learn from neighbors, weakening communal ties. I document a negative county-level association between soil heterogeneity and close-knit communities. Using individual-level data on nineteenth-century domestic migrants, I show that this association is not driven by selective in-migration and document farmers? cultural adaptation using a difference-in-differences framework. Focusing on mechanisms, I show that soil heterogeneity slowed farmers? agricultural learning and prompted those who depended on social networks to migrate elsewhere.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/735506
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/735506
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Pricing of Options and Corporate Liabilities
AU  - Black, Fischer
AU  - Scholes, Myron
Y1  - 1973/05/01
PY  - 1973
DA  - 1973/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260062
DO  - 10.1086/260062
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 637
EP  - 654
VL  - 81
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - If options are correctly priced in the market, it should not be possible to make sure profits by creating portfolios of long and short positions in options and their underlying stocks. Using this principle, a theoretical valuation formula for options is derived. Since almost all corporate liabilities can be viewed as combinations of options, the formula and the analysis that led to it are also applicable to corporate liabilities such as common stock, corporate bonds, and warrants. In particular, the formula can be used to derive the discount that should be applied to a corporate bond because of the possibility of default.
AB  - If options are correctly priced in the market, it should not be possible to make sure profits by creating portfolios of long and short positions in options and their underlying stocks. Using this principle, a theoretical valuation formula for options is derived. Since almost all corporate liabilities can be viewed as combinations of options, the formula and the analysis that led to it are also applicable to corporate liabilities such as common stock, corporate bonds, and warrants. In particular, the formula can be used to derive the discount that should be applied to a corporate bond because of the possibility of default.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260062
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260062
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Bidding for Firms: Subsidy Competition in the United                         States
AU  - Slattery, Cailin
Y1  - 2025/02/24
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/735509
DO  - 10.1086/735509
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2563
EP  - 2614
VL  - 133
IS  - 8
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - State and local governments in the United States compete to attract firms by offering discretionary subsidies. I use a private value English auction to model the subsidy bidding process and quantify the welfare effects of competition. The allocation of rents between states and firms depends on the heterogeneity in states? valuations for firms and the substitutability of locations. I find that competition increases welfare by less than 5% over a subsidy ban, and states compete away the surplus, transferring all of the rents to firms. These findings dampen any interpretation of subsidy competition as an effective place-based policy.
AB  - State and local governments in the United States compete to attract firms by offering discretionary subsidies. I use a private value English auction to model the subsidy bidding process and quantify the welfare effects of competition. The allocation of rents between states and firms depends on the heterogeneity in states? valuations for firms and the substitutability of locations. I find that competition increases welfare by less than 5% over a subsidy ban, and states compete away the surplus, transferring all of the rents to firms. These findings dampen any interpretation of subsidy competition as an effective place-based policy.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/735509
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/735509
Y2  - 2026/04/24
