TY  - JOUR
T1  - Dynamic Pricing Regulation and Welfare in Insurance                         Markets
AU  - Aizawa, Naoki
AU  - Ko, Ami
Y1  - 2025/02/24
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/735512
DO  - 10.1086/735512
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2371
EP  - 2413
VL  - 133
IS  - 8
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - While the traditional role of insurers is to provide protection against individuals? idiosyncratic risks, insurers themselves face substantial uncertainties due to aggregate shocks. To prevent insurers from passing these aggregate risks onto consumers, governments have increasingly adopted dynamic pricing regulations, which limit insurers? ability to change premiums over time. We evaluate dynamic pricing regulation using an equilibrium model of the US long-term care insurance market, featuring insurers? lack of commitment and endogenous market structures. We find that stricter dynamic pricing regulation has a limited impact on improving consumer welfare, while it reduces insurer profits and increases market concentration.
AB  - While the traditional role of insurers is to provide protection against individuals? idiosyncratic risks, insurers themselves face substantial uncertainties due to aggregate shocks. To prevent insurers from passing these aggregate risks onto consumers, governments have increasingly adopted dynamic pricing regulations, which limit insurers? ability to change premiums over time. We evaluate dynamic pricing regulation using an equilibrium model of the US long-term care insurance market, featuring insurers? lack of commitment and endogenous market structures. We find that stricter dynamic pricing regulation has a limited impact on improving consumer welfare, while it reduces insurer profits and increases market concentration.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/735512
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/735512
Y2  - 2026/04/24
